Introduction¶

Why do 30% of patients miss their scheduled appointments?

This project is aim to analyze what factors are important for us to know in order to predict if a patient will show up for their scheduled appointment?.

Dataset Description¶

This dataset(original source on Kaggle) collects information from 100k medical appointments in Brazil and is focused on the question of whether or not patients show up for their appointment. A number of characteristics about the patient are included in each row. Data Dictionary

  • PatientId: Unique identifier for each patient.

  • AppointmentID: Unique identifier for each appointment.

  • Gender: Gender of the patient (M for male, F for female).

  • ScheduledDay: The date and time when the appointment was scheduled.

  • AppointmentDay: The date of the actual appointment.

  • Age: Age of the patient.

  • Neighbourhood: The neighborhood where the appointment is scheduled.

  • Scholarship: Indicates whether the patient is enrolled in the Bolsa Família welfare program (0 for not enrolled, 1 for enrolled).

  • Hipertension: Indicates whether the patient has hypertension (0 for no, 1 for yes).

  • Diabetes: Indicates whether the patient has diabetes (0 for no, 1 for yes).

  • Alcoholism: Indicates whether the patient has alcoholism (0 for no, 1 for yes).

  • Handicap: Indicates the level of handicap of the patient (0 for no handicap, 1-4 for varying degrees of handicap).

  • SMS_received: Indicates whether the patient received an SMS reminder for the appointment (0 for no, 1 for yes).

  • No-show: Indicates whether the patient did not show up for the appointment (No for showed up, Yes for did not show up).

Question for Analysis¶

  • Is there any factor that would impact patients apperance?

  • If yes, what are the main three factors?

Data Wrangling¶

In this section of the report, we will load in the data, check for cleanliness, and then trim and clean the dataset for analysis.

# Create new variables to split the date and time from the ScheduledDay and AppointmentDay, respectively
appoint['ScheduledDate'] = appoint['ScheduledDay'].dt.date
appoint['ScheduledTime'] = appoint['ScheduledDay'].dt.time
appoint['AppointmentDate'] = appoint['AppointmentDay'].dt.date
appoint['AppointmentTime'] = appoint['AppointmentDay'].dt.time


# Create a new variable to show the waiting time between scheduled day and appointment day
appoint['WaitDay'] = (appoint['AppointmentDay'] - appoint['ScheduledDay'] ).dt.days +1

In [777]:
# List of variables to plot
variables = ['SMS_received', 'Scholarship', 'Hipertension', 'Diabetes']

# Create a 2x2 grid of subplots
fig, axes = plt.subplots(2, 2, figsize=(20, 10))

# Loop over each variable and each subplot
for var, ax in zip(variables, axes.flatten()):
    # Create a cross-tabulation of the variable and 'Show'
    data = pd.crosstab(appoint[var], appoint['Show'])
    # Create the bar plot with 'showpct' calculated directly
    sns.barplot(data=data, x=data.index, y=data[1] / data.sum(axis=1) * 100, ax=ax)
    # Set the title, labels, and y-limit
    ax.set_title(f'Show Percentage by {var}')
    ax.set_ylabel('Show Percentage' if ax in [axes[0,0], axes[1,0]] else '')
    ax.set_xlabel(var)
    ax.set_ylim(0, 100)
    ax.set_xticklabels(['No', 'Yes'])

# Adjust the spacing between subplots and show the plot
plt.subplots_adjust(hspace=0.3)
plt.show()

Conclusions¶

I don't find any variable has strong influence on patients apperance from the analysis. The percentage of SHOW is quite similar across SMS_received, Scholarship, Hipertension, and Diabetes(Fig 1). And the percentage of SHOW doesn't have strong trend along Age and WaitDay(Fig 2).

In [783]:
# List of variables to plot
variables = ['SMS_received', 'Scholarship', 'Hipertension', 'Diabetes']

# Create a 2x2 grid of subplots
fig, axes = plt.subplots(2, 2, figsize=(20, 10))

# Loop over each variable and each subplot
for var, ax in zip(variables, axes.flatten()):
    # Create a cross-tabulation of the variable and 'Show'
    data = pd.crosstab(appoint[var], appoint['Show'])
    # Create the bar plot with 'showpct' calculated directly
    sns.barplot(data=data, x=data.index, y=data[1] / data.sum(axis=1) * 100, ax=ax)
    # Set the title, labels, and y-limit
    ax.set_title(f'Show Percentage by {var}')
    ax.set_ylabel('Show Percentage' if ax in [axes[0,0], axes[1,0]] else '')
    ax.set_xlabel(var)
    ax.set_ylim(0, 100)
    ax.set_xticklabels(['No', 'Yes'])

# Set the main title and adjust the spacing between subplots
fig.suptitle('Fig 1: Show Percentage by SMS_received, Scholarship, Hipertension, and Diabetes')
plt.subplots_adjust(hspace=0.3)
plt.show()
